text: I wouldn’t say that I am less likely to trust publish dates in general. I think I am just less likely to trust them on research based pieces. This is where I see the most re-skinning. I understand the reasoning, stats pieces are not fun to write, but it can be very misleading for the reader to pass off 2015 research as 2021 research.

text:
Yes if the value of the topic is contingent upon recency, but not if the topic is evergreen.

In some cases, older content could very well still be relevant and accurate even if it's old, but keeping publish dates on those pieces might unfairly harm perception because we naturally feel newer = better.

text:
Looks like poorly done syndication to me. QuebecNews links back to PennyHoarder via a "source link" at the bottom. The BizNews one links back to PennyHoarder's privacy policy.

In short, it looks like they were trying to do some kind of syndication.... and failed. :rolling_on_the_floor_laughing:

The crappy sites both have their respective URLs set as canonical, so my guess is that these links back to the PennyHoarder are doing absolutely nothing for them. A big ol' waste of time by the person that did this.

text:
They’re just workflow automation tools - if they get abused or ignored they won’t help. But if the underlying outreach strategy is solid then they’ll let you send more emails in less time while maintaining a certain quality level.

So tldr, depends heavily on what type of outreach you use it for.
